solutions.content:
Pretty simple solution using DFS recursion. The idea was to mark the component using negatives and then flip them back in a second pass.

If I didn't want to mess with the initial grid I would create a second result grid. Then do a single pass writing to the result grid and use non-zero values in said grid to track visited cells. As the final step I'd loop through the origional grid to copy over everything missing in the result grid. 
```
class Solution {
    public int[][] colorBorder(int[][] grid, int row, int col, int color) {
        markComponent(grid,row,col,grid[row][col],color);
        fixComponent(grid,row,col);
        return grid;
    }

    int markComponent(int[][] g, int r, int c, int t, int color) {
        if (r < 0 || c < 0 || r == g.length || c == g[0].length || (g[r][c] != t && g[r][c] > 0)) return 0;
        if (g[r][c] > 0) {
            g[r][c] = -t;
            if (markComponent(g,r-1,c,t,color) +
               markComponent(g,r+1,c,t,color) +
               markComponent(g,r,c-1,t,color) +
               markComponent(g,r,c+1,t,color) < 4)
                g[r][c] = -color;
        }
        return 1;
    }

    void fixComponent(int[][] g, int r, int c) {
        if (r < 0 || c < 0 || r == g.length || c == g[0].length || g[r][c] > 0) return;
        g[r][c] = -g[r][c];
        fixComponent(g,r-1,c);
        fixComponent(g,r+1,c);
        fixComponent(g,r,c-1);
        fixComponent(g,r,c+1);
    }
}
```

