solutions.content:
The approach is simple DFS that finds the **connected** component from *r0, c0*. In addition, we need to color the boundary of the connected component with the given *color*.

A **boundary** of a connected component is defined as the boxes which are **surrounded 4-directonally by atleast one box that has a different color** other than that of connected component. Consider an example below to understand the boundary, *r0* = 1, *c0* = 1, *color* = 3.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/eb05a688-bbbd-41e9-90c6-d4eb4c5bf3f3_1597411149.5754387.png)

**Marking Boundary in DFS**
Use a variable to keep track of count of same boxes present in 4-directions. Let it be *same*. It is incremented in two cases:
1. If a box is already visited, then it must be a part of the connected component.
2. When making recursive call for unvisited part of the connected component.

If *same* is less than 4 for a box, change its color to the given *color* as it is the part of the boundary. 
```
class Solution {
public:
    int xDir[4] = {1, 0, -1, 0};
    int yDir[4] = {0, 1, 0, -1};

    void dfs(int r, int c, vector<vector<int>>& grid, bool **visited, int color) {
        visited[r][c] = true;

		// variable to keep track of count of same boxes in 4-directions
        int same = 0;

		// checking 4-directionally
        for(int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
            int i = r + xDir[k], j = c + yDir[k];

            if(i < 0 || i >= grid.size() || j < 0 || j >= grid[0].size())
                continue;

			// if visited, it must a part of the connected component
            if(visited[i][j]) {
                same++;
                continue;
            }

			// recursive call for unvisited part of the connected component
            if(grid[i][j] == grid[r][c]) {
                dfs(i, j, grid, visited, color);
                same++;
            }
        }

		// if it is the part of the boundary
        if(same < 4)
            grid[r][c] = color;
    }

    vector<vector<int>> colorBorder(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int r0, int c0, int color) {
        bool **visited;
        visited = new bool*[grid.size()];

        for(int i = 0; i < grid.size(); i++) {
            visited[i] = new bool[grid[0].size()];

            for(int j = 0; j < grid[0].size(); j++)
                visited[i][j] = false;
        }

        dfs(r0, c0, grid, visited, color);

        return grid;
    }
};

