solutions.content:
Recursion rule: It will enter the next level of recursion only if current point is not a border. 
Each time we check 4 directions, say next point:
* If current point is a border, we would change current point's color and not enter the recursion with this next point, since it already reaches the border. 
* If not, we do not change current color and enter the next level of recursion.

So we do not need to test the boundary in the base case, we only test whether it is visted.

Noted, when test it is a border:
Other than the next point is out of boundary, it also may be an inner point.
If the next point's color is not the original color, we also need to test wehter we have visited before. Because it may be an inner point so that we didn't change its color.

```
class Solution {
    private static final int[][] dir = { {-1,0}, {1,0}, {0,-1}, {0,1} };
    public int[][] colorBorder(int[][] grid, int r0, int c0, int color) {
        boolean[][] visited = new boolean[grid.length][grid[0].length];
        colorBorder(grid, r0, c0, grid[r0][c0], color, visited);
        return grid;
    }
    private void colorBorder(int[][] grid, int r, int c, int orig, int color, boolean[][] visited) {
        if (visited[r][c]) return;
        visited[r][c] = true;
        for (int[] d : dir) {
            int nr = r + d[0], nc = c + d[1]; // next point
            if (nr < 0 || nr == grid.length || nc < 0 || nc == grid[0].length || (grid[nr][nc] != orig && !visited[nr][nc])) {
			// update current color since either the next point is out of boundary or the next point's color is different and we did not visit it before.
                grid[r][c] = color; 
                continue; // not enter the recursion and go next direction.
            }
            colorBorder(grid, nr, nc, orig, color, visited);
        }
    }
}
