# Intuition
The goal is to color the border cells and cells adjacent to different colors with the target color. To achieve this, we can use Breadth-First Search (BFS) starting from the given cell.


# Approach
Push the starting cell coordinates into the queue, mark it as visited, and store its color as the original color.

Perform BFS traversal:

While the queue is not empty, do the following:
Extract the front element from the queue, representing the current cell coordinates.

Check if the current cell is on the border or adjacent to a different color:
Initialize the isBorder flag to check if the cell is on the border (first or last row/column).
Initialize the isAdjacentToDifferentColor flag to track if the cell is adjacent to a different color.

Iterate through the four directions:
Calculate the new row and column coordinates.
If the new coordinates are within the grid boundaries and the cell is unvisited:

Check if the cell has the original color.
If so, push it into the queue, mark it as visited, and continue the BFS traversal.

Otherwise, set the isAdjacentToDifferentColor flag to true.
If the current cell is on the border or adjacent to a different color, update its color to the target color.

After the BFS traversal is complete, return the modified grid.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
 O(n * m)
- Space complexity:
 O(n * m)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int m,n;
    int delr[4] = {0, 0, 1, -1};
    int delc[4] = {1, -1, 0, 0};

    vector<vector<int>> colorBorder(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int row, int col, int color) {
        m = grid.size();
        n = grid[0].size();
        int originalColor = grid[row][col];
        vector<vector<bool>> visited(m, vector<bool>(n, false));
        queue<pair<int, int>> q;
        q.push({row, col});
        visited[row][col] = true;

        while (!q.empty()) {
            int r = q.front().first;
            int c = q.front().second;
            q.pop();
            //checking if the row or coloumn are border or not, initially keeping it false.
            bool isb=false;
            if(r == 0 || r == m - 1 || c == 0 || c ==n - 1)
            isb =true;
            //initially we keep adj as false, this tells us whether the cell is adjacent to some cell which is not of the same color to any side, that is the outline of the connected component.
            bool isad = false;

            for (int k = 0; k < 4; k++) {
                //iterating on all 4 directions
                int nr = r + delr[k];
                int nc = c + delc[k];

                if (nr >= 0 && nc >= 0 && nr < m && nc < n) {
                    if (!visited[nr][nc]) {
                        //checking if the new cell is connected component or not, if yes, we take it into consideration for the next iteration and push in the queue.
                        if (grid[nr][nc] == originalColor) {
                            q.push({nr, nc});
                            visited[nr][nc] = true;
                        } else {
                            //if not connected then we have found one cell which is the outline of the connected component.
                            isad = true;
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
            //at last we are just coloring all the cells are which are either border cells or the outline of the connected component.
            if (isb || isad) {
                grid[r][c] = color;
            }
        }

        return grid;
    }
};
```

