****Binary Indexed Tree (BIT):
****
Purpose: The Binary Indexed Tree, also known as a Fenwick Tree, is used to efficiently perform prefix sum queries and updates. It helps keep track of the number of digits that have been removed from the original string, which is essential for selecting and processing digits during the optimization process.
How It's Used:
The BIT is initialized with a size of 'n+1,' where 'n' is the number of elements (positions in the string).
The update method is used to increment the value at a specific index (position) by a given delta (usually 1). This operation marks that a digit has been removed from the original string.
The query method is used to efficiently compute the prefix sum up to a specific index. It helps determine how many digits have been removed from positions preceding a given position.
Queues (qs - Vector of Queues):
**
Purpose: Queues **are used to keep track of the positions of each digit in the original string. Each queue corresponds to a digit from 0 to 9, and it stores the positions of that digit in the string.
How They're Used:
During the initialization of qs, each digit's queue is populated with its respective positions in the original string.
The queues are used to efficiently select and process digits during the process of minimizing the integer:
Digits that can be moved to the left-hand side (i.e., smaller digits that have sufficient available swaps) are selected from their respective queues and added to the result.
Positions of processed digits are marked as "removed" in the BIT using the update method.
This process continues until 'k' swaps are exhausted or no more valid swaps are possible.

# Code
```
class BIT {
public:
    int n;               // Number of elements
    vector<int> nodes;   // Binary Indexed Tree (Fenwick Tree)

    BIT(int n) {
        this->n = n;
        nodes = vector<int>(n + 1);  // Initialize the BIT with size (n + 1)
    }

    // Function to update a value at index 'i' by adding 'delta'
    void update(int i, int delta) {
        ++i;  // Increment 'i' to convert 0-based indexing to 1-based indexing
        while (i <= n) {
            nodes[i] += delta;  // Update the BIT node at index 'i' by adding 'delta'
            i += (i & -i);     // Move to the parent node (next node with a higher significant bit)
        }
    }

    // Function to query the prefix sum up to index 'i'
    int query(int i) {
        ++i;  // Increment 'i' to convert 0-based indexing to 1-based indexing
        int sum = 0;
        while (i > 0) {
            sum += nodes[i];   // Accumulate the sum from the current node
            i -= (i & -i);    // Move to the previous node (next node with a lower significant bit)
        }
        return sum;
    }
};

class Solution {
public:
    string minInteger(string num, int k) {
        vector<queue<int>> qs(10);  // An array of queues to store positions of each digit
        int n = num.size();

        // Populate queues with the positions of each digit
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            qs[num[i] - '0'].push(i);
        }

        string lhs;  // Left-hand side of the result string
        vector<bool> removed(n, false);  // Indicates if a digit has been removed from the original string
        BIT* tree = new BIT(n);  // Create a Binary Indexed Tree (BIT) to track removed digits

        while (k > 0) {
            bool found = false;
            for (int d = 0; d <= 9; ++d) {
                if (!qs[d].empty()) {
                    int pos = qs[d].front();  // Get the position of the current digit
                    int shifted = tree->query(pos - 1);  // Query the BIT to find the number of removed digits before pos
                    if (pos - shifted <= k) {
                        k -= pos - shifted;  // Update remaining swaps
                        tree->update(pos, 1);  // Mark the current digit as removed in the BIT
                        qs[d].pop();  // Remove the position from the queue
                        lhs += ('0' + d);  // Append the digit to the left-hand side
                        removed[pos] = true;  // Mark the digit as removed
                        found = true;
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
            if (!found) break;  // If no valid swap is possible, exit the loop
        }

        string rhs;  // Right-hand side of the result string
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            if (!removed[i]) {
                rhs += num[i];  // Append the remaining digits to the right-hand side
            }
        }

        return lhs + rhs;  // Concatenate the left-hand and right-hand sides to form the final result
    }
};

```

