solutions.content:
A solution with **O(n*sqrt(n))** time and  **O(n)** space complexity. 
It is asymptotically slower than the Segment Tree solution,
but it has not been offered so far, so I will add it here for completeness.

We create queues of index occurences for every digit, and we pick the left most index of the smallest digit we could move to first position.
Once we have exhausted all k swaps, we append remaining unused digits.

When we do swaps to move an element to the front, all elements to the left of it shift one position to the right.
To keep track of how far every element has shifted we use a Sqrt Decomposition structure (we could use instead a Segment Tree for this purpose, see other solutions). 
Sqrt Decomposition is a simpler structure, but less efficient too: **calculateShift()** has a **sqrt(n)** instead of **log(n)** execution time. For more information see https://cp-algorithms.com/data_structures/sqrt_decomposition.html



```
// O(n*sqrt(n)) time, O(n) space	
class Solution {	

    public String minInteger(String num, int k) {	
        int n = num.length();	
        char[] arr = num.toCharArray();	

        Queue[] indexQueues = createIndexQueues(arr);	
        SqrtDecomposition sqrt = new SqrtDecomposition(n);	

        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();	
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {	
            if (k == 0) break;	
            for (int digit = 0; digit < 10; digit++) {	
                Queue<Integer> q = indexQueues[digit];	
                if (!q.isEmpty()) {	
                    int originalIndex = q.peek();	
                    int shiftedIndex = originalIndex + sqrt.calculateShift(originalIndex) - i;	
                    if (shiftedIndex <= k) {	
                        sb.append(arr[originalIndex]);	
                        sqrt.add(q.poll());	
                        k -= shiftedIndex;	
                        break;	
                    }    	
                }	
            }            	
        }	

        //add digits which we haven't used yet    	
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) if (sqrt.a[i] == 0) sb.append(arr[i]);	
        return sb.toString();	
    }	

    private Queue[] createIndexQueues(char[] arr) {	
        Queue[] queues = new LinkedList[10];	
        for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) queues[i] = new LinkedList<Integer>();	
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) queues[arr[i]-'0'].offer(i);	
        return queues;	
    }	
}	

//For explanation on how Sqrt Decomposition works, see https://cp-algorithms.com/data_structures/sqrt_decomposition.html
class SqrtDecomposition {	
    int[] a;	
    int[] b;	
    int n;	
    int sqrtN;	

    SqrtDecomposition(int n) {	
        this.n = n;
        sqrtN = ((int) Math.sqrt(n)) + 1;	
        a = new int[n];	
        b = new int[sqrtN];	
    }	

    void add(int i) {	
        a[i]++;	
        b[i/sqrtN]++;	
    }	

    int calculateShift(int i) {	
        int answer = 0;	
        while ( i < n && i % sqrtN != 0) {	
            answer += a[i++];	
        }	
        int j = i/sqrtN;	
        while (j < sqrtN) {	
            answer += b[j++];	
        }	
        return answer;	
    }	
}	
```

