"There will be at most two digits after the decimal point in `hour`." - This means `hour`>= `dist.length - 1 + 0.01`, if there is a valid speed. Therefore, the max speed is no more than  `10 ^ 5 / 0.01 = 10 ^ 7`, and the search space for speed is `[1, 10 ^ 7]`.

**Note:** use`(dist + speed - 1) / speed` to compute the ceil of the time of taking a train.
```java
    public int minSpeedOnTime(int[] dist, double hour) {
        int lo = 1, hi = 10_000_001, n = dist.length;
        while (lo < hi) {
            int speed = lo + hi >> 1;
            double time = 0;
            for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; ++i) { // time need for all but last train.
                time += (dist[i] + speed - 1) / speed;
            }
            time += (double)dist[n - 1] / speed; // The last train will not need to wait.
            if (time > hour) { // slow speed cost more time, search in higher speed space.
                lo = speed + 1;
            }else { // fast speed cost less time, search in lower speed space.
                hi = speed;
            }
        }
        return lo == 10_000_001 ? -1 : lo;
    }
```

