solutions.content:
# Intuition
Understanding the problem statement and knowing that velocity = distance / time. Due to the monotonicity of the problem's constraint that all trains must travel at a minimum speed to reach the office on time, **binary searching** over train velocities or speeds is feasible.
# Approach
How **monotonic** in nature? 

If we increase the speed of the trains, then the time taken for each train ride will decrease, meaning that we'll reach the office earlier. Thus, if it is possible to reach the office on time with a certain speed, then it is also possible to reach the office on time with any speed greater than that. 

The valid lambda function harnesses the math relation, vel = dist / time
It checks whether possible to reach the office on time with a given velocity. It takes as input a velocity value and returning a boolean that indicates whether it is possible to reach the office on time with that speed.

Calculating the total time taken to reach the office by summing up the time taken by each train ride. For each train ride except the last one, it calculates the time taken as the distance of the train ride divided by velocity, rounding up to the nearest integer. This is because each train can only depart at an integer hour, so we may need to wait in between each train ride. Here comes an **edge case**.
For the last train ride, it calculates the time taken as the distance of the train ride divided by the speed, without rounding it up as we don't need to wait after the last train ride.

After calculating the total time taken to reach the office, the function compares it with the given hour value and returns 1 if the total time is less than or equal to hour, and 0 otherwise. 
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
Time complexity is O(n * log(mxv)) where the maximum possible velocity in the binary search be denoted by mxv as it is used to define the max search space(r)
mxv = (1e7+7).

- Space complexity:
O(1)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minSpeedOnTime(vector<int>& dist, double hour) {
        ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(NULL); cout.tie(NULL); 
        int n((int)dist.size());
        auto valid = [&](int vel) -> bool {
            double t(0.0);
            for (int i(0); i <= n-2; ++i) 
                t += (dist[i] + vel - 1) / vel;
            t += (double)dist[n-1] / vel;
            return t <= hour;
        };

        int l(1), r((int)1e7+7), mid, ans(-1);
        while(l <= r) 
            mid = (l + r) >> 1,
            (valid(mid))? (ans = mid, r = mid-1) : l = mid + 1;

        return ans;
    }
};

```

