# Intuition
At first I tried to use brutefore iterating over all available velocities starting from 1 and going to $$10^7$$.

It didn't turn out well...

# Approach

The main idea behind this algorithm is not to use bruteforce. Using binary search over all available velocities we can fastly determine minimum velocity in $$O(n log m)$$.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(n log m)$$ where m is upper bound of velocity

- Space complexity:
$$O(1)$$

# Code
```
public class Solution
{
    public int MinSpeedOnTime(int[] dist, double hour)
    {
        int start = 1;
        int end = 10_000_000 + 1;
        int velocity;
        int minVelocity = int.MaxValue;
        double timeSpent;

        while (start < end)
        {
            timeSpent = 0;
            velocity = (start + end) / 2;

            for (int i = 0; i < dist.Length; i++)
            {
                if (i == dist.Length - 1)
                {
                    timeSpent += (double)dist[i] / (double)velocity;
                }
                else
                {
                    timeSpent += Math.Ceiling((double)dist[i] / velocity);
                }
            }

            if (timeSpent <= hour)
            {
                end = velocity;
                if (velocity < minVelocity)
                {
                    minVelocity = velocity;
                }
            }
            else
            {
                start = velocity + 1;
            }
        }

        if (minVelocity == int.MaxValue)
        {
            return -1;
        }

        return minVelocity;
    }
}
```

