# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Limit the search space. The high end is max dist, the low end is average speed.

Since for `n - 1` rides only integer hours considered, count and prefix sum the dists at first, then `f(intHour, speed) = distcount[intHour * speed] - distcount[(intHour - 1) * speed]` is the count of all dists which will spend `intHour` time for given `speed`. And `f(intHour, speed) * intHour` gives the hours needed.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(hlog(distmax - avgspeed))$$ where `distmax` is high end of search, `avgspeed` is low end. `h` is integer hours and related to the speed being searched: `distmax / speed`

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(c)$$ for dists count, $$10^5$$ constant

# Runtime
6ms

# Code
```
class Solution {

    public int minSpeedOnTime(int[] dist, double hour) {
        int n = dist.length;
        int last = n - 1;

        // Hour limit must be greater than `n - 1`,
        // otherwise there is no way to arrive on time
        if (hour <= last) {
            return -1;
        }

        int distmax = 0;
        long distsum = 0;
        int[] distcount = new int[100_000 + 1];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            distmax = Math.max(distmax, dist[i]);
            distsum += dist[i];
            distcount[dist[i]]++;
        }

        // When hour limit is greater than sum of dist, speed 1 is enough
        if (hour >= distsum) {
            return 1;
        }
        // When hour between (n - 1, n], means `n - 1` trains need spend exactly `n - 1` hours (1 hour for each),
        // thus distmax is minimum speed required. Also consider fraction hour spent by last train.
        if (hour <= n) {
            return Math.max(distmax, divide(dist[last], hour - last));
        }
        // When only 1 ride, average speed is the minimum speed
        int avgspeed = divide(distsum, hour);
        if (n == 1) {
            return avgspeed;
        }

        // The `distcount` is used to calculate integer hours of `n - 1` rides, need exclude last ride
        distcount[dist[last]]--;
        for (int i = 1; i <= distmax; i++) {
            // prefix sum
            distcount[i] += distcount[i - 1];
        }

        // Now hour > n, average speed is low end of search space, `distmax` is the high end
        int low = avgspeed, high = distmax;

        while (low <= high) {
            int speed = (high + low) >>> 1;

            // distcount[speed] is count of all dists <= speed, which will spend 1 integer hour for each
            int time = distcount[speed];
            int hourmax = (int) Math.ceil((double) distmax / speed);
            for (int intHour = 2; intHour <= hourmax; intHour++) {
                // distcount[intHour * speed] - distcount[(intHour - 1) * speed] is count of all dists within
                // ((intHour-1) * speed, intHour * speed], which will spend intHour time for each
                time += intHour * (distcount[Math.min(distmax, intHour * speed)] - distcount[(intHour - 1) * speed]);
            }

            if (time + (double) dist[last] / speed > hour) {
                // Exceed hour limit, increase speed
                low = speed + 1;
            } else {
                // Within hour limit, decrease speed to find minimum
                high = speed - 1;
            }
        }

        return low;
    }

    private int divide(long dist, double hour) {
        hour = Math.round(hour * 100);
        return (int) Math.ceil(dist * 100 / hour);
    }
}
```

