solutions.content:
The first code below is a prefix sum and binary search algorithm, which is from what was the fastest bar on the runtime graph.  The code was modified to run faster.  My slower original code is the second code sample, which runs in 18ms.

**Algorithm**

1. If only one train, then return easy calculation of speed for that train.
2. If required hours is more than the number of trains-1, then no solution so return -1.
3. Get the maximum distance for any train to travel (`maxDist`).
4. If the needed speed is greater than `maxDist`, then directly calculate the speed and return.
5. Calculate the count of trains at each distance.
6. Calculate the prefix sums of the count of trains at each distance.
7. Set binary search limits to 1..maxDist.
8. If `maxDist` is big, then try to optimize binary search limits by factors of 10.
9. Loop to do a binary search to test different proposed speed values (`mid` value in binary search) to find the lowest speed that arrives at the office at or before the required hours.
10. Return the result of the binary search, which is the slowest integer speed that is sufficient to get to the office in time.

**Explanation of Algorithm step #4**

Before starting the binary search, check if the answer speed for this test case is greater than the maximum distance for any train to travel (`maxDist`).  If the answer speed will be `maxDist` or greater, then we can simply and directly calculate the actual speed required to get to work exactly on time WITHOUT a binary search.  If this calculated speed is greater than 10e7, then return -1 because the leetcode problem gives 10e7 as the maximum valid speed.  Otherwise return the calculated speed.  We can do this simple calculation for the speed because with a speed of `maxDist` or higher, the time between taking any two trains will always be between 0 and 1, rounded up to 1 hour.  The total time to get to work will therefore be the number of trains, except the last train, plus the distance of the last train, divided by the as yet unknown speed of the train:

`timeToWork = (dist.length - 1) + dist[dist.length-1] / speed`

Solving for speed will give:

`speed = dist[dist.length-1] / (timeToWork - dist.length + 1)`

This will give the speed required to get to work exactly on time.  But because the problem requires returning an integer speed, do a ceiling on the calculated speed, minus a tiny value to handle floating-point calculation errors due to non-exact representation of a theoretical mathematical value into a floating-point double.

If useful, please upvote.

**-------- From fastest code on runtime graph (July 29, 2023), then modified to run at 4ms --------**
```
class Solution {
    public int minSpeedOnTime(int[] dist, double hour) {
        final int last = dist.length - 1;
        if (dist.length == 1)  return (int)Math.ceil(dist[0] / hour - 0.00000005);
        if (hour <= last)  return -1;

        int maxDist = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < last; i++) 
            maxDist = Math.max(maxDist, dist[i]);

        if ((double)(last) + (double)dist[last] / maxDist > hour) {
            double speed = Math.ceil((double)dist[last] / (hour - last) - 0.000001);
            return (speed > 10_000_000) ? -1 : (int)speed;
        }

        int[] sums = new int[maxDist + 1];
        for (int i = 0; i < last; i++)  sums[dist[i]]++;
        for (int i = 1; i <= maxDist; i++) sums[i] += sums[i - 1];

        int left = 1;
        int right = maxDist;
        if (maxDist >= 1000) {
            while (left * 10 < right && !onTime(left * 10, dist, sums, hour, maxDist))  left *= 10;
            while (right / 10 > left && onTime(right / 10, dist, sums, hour, maxDist))  right /= 10;
        }

        while (left <= right) {
            int mid = (left + right) / 2;
            if (onTime(mid, dist, sums, hour, maxDist))
                right = mid - 1;
            else
                left = mid + 1;
        }
        return left;
    }

    private boolean onTime(int speed, int[] dist, int[] sums, double hour, int maxDist) {
        int curTime = sums[speed];
        int limit = (maxDist + speed - 1) / speed;
        for (int i = 2; i <= limit; i++) 
            curTime += i * (sums[Math.min(maxDist, i * speed)] - sums[i * speed - speed]);
        return (double)curTime + (double)dist[dist.length - 1] / speed <= hour;
    }
}
```


